## Is the Hearts and Arrows Premium Worth It?

**The premium is worth it if all three of the following are true:**

1. You are buying at a price point where 10–30% more money does not create financial strain — roughly $4,500+ budget for a 1ct round
2. You can verify the diamond is a true 8×8 H&A through an in-person viewer test or through documentation from a recognized certifying organization (AGS zero-ideal, GCAL Ideal, or H&A brand like Brian Gavin or Whiteflash)
3. The precision craftsmanship is personally meaningful to you — you care about gemological quality the way a watch collector cares about the movement quality visible only through the caseback

**The premium is not worth it if any of the following are true:**

- The jeweler cannot show you the H&A viewer result in real time
- The "H&A" designation appears only in the jeweler's product description, not in any independent certification
- Your budget is under $4,000 and the 10–30% premium would otherwise fund a cut, color, or clarity upgrade that is more visible
- You have never looked at a diamond through an H&A viewer and do not know what a "true 8×8" looks like

For reference: a [GIA Excellent G-VS1 round at $3,200](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28915027?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) on Blue Nile is a beautiful, high-performing diamond. See the [1 carat round diamond price audit](/1-carat-round-diamond-price) for a complete breakdown of what each price tier delivers. The Excellent cut grade puts it within the broader H&A proportion range even if it does not produce a perfect 8×8 pattern. For most buyers, this stone outperforms any "H&A" stone that cannot be verified as a true 8×8.

Similarly, a [GIA Excellent G-VVS2 at $3,760](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27622805?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) represents the upper range of the sweet spot for natural 1ct round brilliants. The VVS2 clarity here is a luxury upgrade over VS1 — but it places you at a price level where the H&A premium ($376–$1,128 additional) starts to be a real decision.

